─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 LICENSING RATIONALE FOR FIRMWARE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Core 0 and Core 1 run on physically separate processor cores (RP2350B dual-core
Cortex-M33). They communicate exclusively through the IPC protocol defined in
firmware/shared/ipc/ipc_protocol.h. This boundary is maintained at both the
source level (Core 1 contains no Meshtastic #includes) and the build level
(separate CMake targets).

This design mirrors the separation between a GPL-licensed kernel and a
non-GPL userspace recognised by the FSF GPL FAQ:

  "If the modules are designed to run in the same address space and do
   intimate things with each other they form a single combined program, ...
   but if they communicate at arm's length through a well-defined interface
   they can be separate programs."
                                     — GNU GPL FAQ, fsf.org

The IPC protocol header (MIT) is compatible with both GPL-3.0 and Apache-2.0,
serving as the neutral interface between the two cores without license conflict.
